frameDefinitions: A Wearer wears accessories, which are made of  some Material and may have a Style.
The words in this frame refer to facial Expressions and the Possessors of those Expressions.
The Payer is (legally) forced to pay a Fine by an official Speaker as a punishment for some action (the Reason).
This frame contains words referring to items of food.
A Cognizer has a piece of Content in their model of the world.
This frame contains nouns that refer to sensations in different modalities.
frameExamples: She wore a black velvet <t>hat</t> on her head.
They were <t>fined</t> approximately $3.1 billion dollars for their knowing, malicious injury to consumers.
Specialties include deep fried shredded beef , duck , prawn dishes and hand-made <t>noodles</t>.
Your boss is <t>aware</t> of your commitment.
The huge sand dunes, perpetually changing, make for a surreal <t>sight</t>.
listRoleDefinitions: This role identifies  the <fen>Accoutrement</fen>.
This is the <fen>Expression</fen> made.
This is the person who exhibitis the <fen>Expression</fen>.
The emotion that is conveyed by a particular <fen>Expression</fen>.
The <fen>Speaker</fen> is the person who imposes the <fen>Fine</fen> upon the <fen>Payer</fen>.
The <fen>Payer</fen> is the person or thing about whom/which a judgment is made.  With verbs this role is typically expressed as Object:

Typically, there is a constituent expressing the <t>Reason</t> for the Judge's judgment. It is usually a <ment>for</ment>-PP, e.g. I <t>admire</t> you <fex name='Reason'>for your intellect</fex>. For some words in this domain, the Reason frame element is obligatory. That is to say, the overt expression of this frame element may only be omitted when the reason for the judgment is understood from context. For example, the sentence 'I <t>blame</t> you!' can only be uttered when it is clear what the addressee is being blamed for.
The money given to expiate some debt for transgression.
When the event occurs.
Where the event takes place.

The <fen>Cognizer</fen> is the person whose awareness of phenomena is at question. With a target verb or adjective the <fen>Cognizer</fen> is generally expressed as an External Argument with the <fen>Content</fen> expressed as an Object or Complement.
The <fen>Content</fen> is the object of the <fen>Cognizer</fen>'s awareness. <fen>Content</fen> can be expressed as a direct object or in a PP Complement.
Some verbs in this frame allow a <fen>Topic</fen> to be expressed in about-PPs.
<fen>Expressor</fen> is the body part that reveals the <fen>Cognizer</fen>'s state to the observer.
The time interval during which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> is aware of the <fen>Content</fen>.
This role is only expressed with certain nouns in this frame, and then only with the help of a support verb, such as <ment>have</ment>:

This is the entity or phenomenon which gives rise to the sensation. In cases of veridical sensation, this role is not typically distinguished from <fen>Percept</fen>. Most of the phrases that express this role can be paraphrased as <ment>from</ment>-phrases, e.g.

The role <fen>Percept</fen> is used for phrases that express the characteristic property of a sensation. Typically this characteristic property is described with reference to the entity or phenomenon that produces the sensation---that  is why this role can be difficult to distinguish from Source. It is possible for Source and Percept to be expressed separately, however:

This role is assigned to phrases expressing the body part in which a sensation is located. Since touch is the least localized of sense modalities, words relating to haptic sensations are the ones most likely to occur with this FE:
This role is the perceptual background against which the Phenomenon is experienced by the Perceiver.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the sensation is perceived.
listRoleExamples: The mental control officer fined <fex>you</fex> for your lack of diligence.
<fex>Your boss</fex> is aware of your commitment.
Your boss is aware <fex>of your commitment</fex>.

This herb gives off a smell <fex>of garlic</fex>.
I have a tingling feeling <fex>in my hands</fex>.
